In 1991, the agreement on a civilian government inaugurated a constitutional democracy and the country's reintegration into the international community, and in 1992 political parties were established, a real democratic process begun and Mali became a regional and international reference point. Economic growth proved insufficient for social progress, especially for the vast average population with unmet basic needs. This situation has led to the marginalization, growing food insecurity3 and underdevelopment of the majority of the population in rural areas. The economic situation, together with other factors, has led to frequent social unrest and the need for social cohesion. Challenging the power of the military, rebellions broke out across the country. They radically altered the country's social economic and security environment.
In 2012, together with the situation in neighbouring countries and throughout the Sahelian region, this seems to be the worst situation in the last 50 years, and can be summed up, if we consider the situation at national and sub-
national levels. The Malian authorities see reports on complex emergencies created throughout the year mainly by the Islamic terrorist group Al-Qaeda for the Islamic Maghreb (Al Qaeda in the Maghret) (QAM)4 and the Movement for Unity and Jihad in West Africa (MUJAO), who brought with them many transnational jihadis with different degrees of training.
